{{Infobox artist | name = Terry Fenton | image = | imagesize = 260px | caption = A painting by Terry Fenton in the Edmonton Contemporary Artists' Society 2013 exhibition | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|7|1}} | birth_place = [[Regina, Saskatchewan]] | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = [[Canadians|Canadian]] | field = [[painting]], [[writing]], [[Curator|curating]] | training = [[University of Regina]], [[Emma Lake Artists' Workshops]], | movement = [[landscape painting]], [[modernism]], | works = | patrons = [[University of Lethbridge]]
}} '''Terry Fenton''' (born July 1, 1940) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] artist,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blouinartinfo.com/artists/218187-terry-fenton|title=Biography of Terry Fenton - BLOUIN ARTINFO, The Premier Global Online Destination for Art and Culture - BLOUIN ARTINFO|publisher=}}</ref> author, critic,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ccca.concordia.ca/cv/english/fenton-cv.html|title=Terry Fenton|publisher=}}</ref> and curator<ref name="TO">{{cite web|url=http://www.torontopubliclibrary.ca/detail.jsp?Entt=RDM1434289&R=1434289|title=Walter Darby Bannard : an exhibition organized by Terry Fenton, the Edmonton Art Gallery. --|first=Bannard, Walter Darby,|last=1934-|publisher=}}</ref> known for his landscape paintings,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artistsincanada.com/article/?q=242|title=Terry Fenton's - Big Sky Country|publisher=}}</ref> his support of [[modernist]] art,<ref name="TO" /> and his writing on the work of artists such as [[Jack Bush]], [[Anthony Caro]], [[Peter Hide]], [[Dorothy Knowles]], [[Ken Macklin]], [[Kenneth Noland]], [[Jules Olitski]], and [[William Perehudoff]].<ref name="ARTSask">{{cite web|url=http://www.artsask.ca/en/artists/terry_fenton|title=ArtSask|first=|last=ArtSask|publisher=}}</ref><ref name="FentonW">{{cite web|url=http://www.sharecom.ca/fenton/writingindex.html|title=Terry Fenton: writing on art|first=Terry|last=Fenton|publisher=}}</ref><ref name="CanEn">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/author/696|title=Terry Fenton - The Canadian Encyclopedia|publisher=}}</ref> Fenton is the former director of the [[Edmonton Art Gallery]] (1972 - 1987), the A.C. Leighton Foundation, [[Calgary]] (1987 - 1993) and the [[Mendel Art Gallery]], [[Saskatoon]] (1993 - 1997).<ref name="AA">{{cite web|url=http://www.askart.com/artist/Terry_Fenton/11008902/Terry_Fenton.aspx|title=Terry Fenton - Artist, Fine Art Prices, Auction Records for Terry Fenton|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.odonwagnergallery.com/artist/terry-fenton|title=Terry Fenton art - Odon Wagner Contemporary|publisher=}}</ref> Since 2013, Fenton has resided in [[Victoria, British Columbia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://canadianart.ca/exhibitions/terry-fenton-land-and-sea/|title=Terry Fenton: LAND and SEA - Canadian Art|publisher=}}</ref>
== Education == Terry Fenton was born in [[Regina, Saskatchewan]] in 1940, and studied at Regina College's School of Fine Art (now [[University of Regina]]) from 1958-1960, with [[Ronald Bloore]], [[Roy Kiyooka]], and [[Arthur McKay]]. Moving to the Saskatoon campus to study English literature, Fenton earned his Bachelor of Arts degree in 1962. Along with studies at the University of Regina (1965-1966), Fenton attended [[Emma Lake Artist's Workshops]] in Saskatchewan with [[John Cage]] and [[Lawrence Alloway]] in 1965, [[Frank Stella]] in 1967, and Michael Steiner in 1969.<ref name="SNAC">{{cite web|url=http://www.sknac.ca/index.php?page=ArtistDetail&id=307|title=Saskatchewan NAC Artists - Terry Fenton|first=|last=Squareflo.com|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://bugeramathesongallery.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Terry-Fenton-Bio-2014.pdf Bugera Matheson Gallery, Terry Fenton: Biography]</ref>
== Painting == The imagery in Terry Fenton's paintings is often focused on the large skies and wide open prairies of his home province. In Fenton's own words, "''Because of their apparent lack of scenery, the open prairies haven't been much painted by anyone. Even painters who've flourished in Saskatchewan have preferred the river valleys in the plains or the aspen parkland and forest to the north and east. While I admire and have absorbed much from them, I'm drawn south and west to the grasslands, partly because I was born and raised in Regina, but especially because the colour and light there is so luminous.''"<ref name="SNAC" /> Fenton's paintings can be found in a number of collections, including the [[University of Lethbridge]], Alberta; the [[MacKenzie Art Gallery]], Regina; the [[Art Gallery of Greater Victoria]], British Columbia; and the Canada Council Art Bank, Ottawa.<ref name="TFCV">{{cite web|url=http://www.sharecom.ca/fenton/cv.html|title=Terry Fenton Curriculum Vitae|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artcyclopedia.com/artists/fenton_terry.html|title=Terry Fenton Online|publisher=}}</ref>
== Writing == Terry Fenton's writing on art has touched on subjects both historical and contemporary, from essays on [[Fayum mummy portraits]]<ref>[http://www.sharecom.ca/fenton/fayuum.html Terry Fenton, ''"PRE-PICTURES? Roman Portraits from FAYUUM"'']</ref> and [[Giovanni Bellini]]'s ''[[St. Francis in Ecstasy (Bellini)|St. Francis in Ecstasy]],''<ref>[http://www.sharecom.ca/fenton/bellini.html Terry Fenton, ''"St. Francis in Ecstasy"'']</ref> to articles on [[Morris Louis]]<ref>[http://www.sharecom.ca/fenton/louis.html Terry Fenton, ''"Morris Louis"'']</ref> and [[Adolph Gottlieb]].<ref>[http://www.sharecom.ca/fenton/gottlieb.html Terry Fenton, ''"Adolph Gottlieb"'']</ref> Fenton has written a number of books, including monographs on [[Dorothy Knowles]], [[Reta Cowley]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hagiospress.com/books/detail/land-marks-the-art-of-dorothy-knowles|title=Hagios Press|publisher=}}</ref> [[Anthony Caro]] and [[Kenneth Noland]], as well as his 2009 treatise on pictorial art, "About Pictures."
